<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
this isn't about comparison. if you're in a group, in 99% of the situations (at least past newbie levels) you SHOULD NOT BE MELEEING. <P>that's not to say shamans CAN'T melee. remember, most shaman races are big fatsos with high innate combat stats. I've played a ogre shaman to level 40 and when needed, I can and do melee. I whip out a big 2hb and pop the enemy over 100 a hit (sometimes). of course I have tons of buffs up, because I CAN. and my pet is there too, chewing away at the enemy's health -- not to mention the dots, debuffs, and DD's I can use on teh enemy.<P>in a group, don't tank (with some exceptions like when a pull goes haywire etc). but in solo situations, its a viable option.<P>1) buff self<BR>2) buff pet<BR>3) dot/debuff enemy<BR>4) melee it to death (with the pet's help)<P>you can come away with *quite* favorable results against blues doing this, because while a shaman isn't a warrior, he is durable and can do a LOT of things a warrior cant (buff pet dott debuff etc).<P>it's all about slanting the odds in your favor. with DDs and pets and debuffs, and buffs on yourself and your pet, you shift thoes odds in your favor. so meleeing is a very viable option for a shaman soloing (and a few other contexts perhaps).<P>Matt
</FONT>
