<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
As far as pulling things off a caster, except for enchanters, casters shouldn't be getting aggroed anyway, unless they are casting too early in the battle.  This of course, a large percentage of offensive casters do, leading inevitably to the conclusion that they often suck.<P>If a caster is simply unlucky enough to get aggro even while playing well, or if I'm in one of my rare good moods, then I will pull a mob off a caster.  I don't know why people mentioned this as a reason for shamans to melee; it's a special situation and painfully obvious.  Just like when you're in a small group.  I think we were talking FULL groups here, without any special situations.<P>There are other obvious situations of course, like when you have full mana and nothing really to use it for.<P>But generally, I find I can help more with a heal(if not for this pull, then the next one -- canni anyone?)  Do any of you guys ever watch your clerics or druids to see how often they are casting, or ask them their mana?  I often contribute heals so that they can catch up on their mana.  This can make the whole group healthier over time.  When I fight, I think of the resources the entire group has, not just what I have.  I worry about the mana of the other guy, as well as myself.  Similarly, I often cast a regrowth or chloro on a tank or three, or even on tanks from other groups in a multi-group camp.  This helps save lives and save cleric and druid mana.  Can the same often be said of my melee contribution?<P>I also sometimes throw in an envenomed bolt DOT.  1100-ish damage in what, 42 seconds is it?  I'm an ogre with strength at about 214 now, maxed out in all melee stats, with a blight hammer and a drakkel icegrinder for 2h blunt, all the top shaman spears except for epic and whatever might turn up in Dragon's necropolis, and iksar beserker club for 1h blunt, and have even fought with an FBSS compounding my alacrity or chanter hastes, and still it's hard to beat the damage a nice high DOT can do -- or frankly, even come close.  By the time the DOT wears off, I've regenned enough mana to cast another.<P>Doing either of these things contributes much more than my melee does, and I'm as excellent as you can be at melee, with AC over 900, and an ogre to boot -- everything maxed, all good weapons.<P>People in their 30's may find meleeing in a group more useful because they aren't fighting mobs that have 7000 hitpoints yet, or have superior heal, envenomed bolt, or regrowth yet, or find malo necessary.<P>But for the rest of us, I think usually if you can't find a way to use your ability to regen mana to shore up everything the group does -- and contribute more that way to it than you ever will with melee -- you probably aren't being creative enough.  I'm proud of what I can do with my blight hammer too, but really, if I'm fighting tough mobs, its damage doesn't count for much even when it proc's.  <P>And the icegrinder in groups?  No wisdom on that, and you've given up the wisdom of a shield and a 1-hand weapon to get it, as well as precious AC.  I find many situations come down to the extra mana and AC you have, especially if one of your group members dies and you find yourself suddenly minus a powerful asset, or if you get multiple pulls, or trained, or lagged, or...well, it just comes in handy.  Much more handy, over time, than a bunch of shaman melee hits, even if they are for 100.  So icegrinder seems an especially poor choice to wield when grouped, for the most part.  Are there special exceptions?  Perhaps, but that doesn't negate my point.<P>I think some of you guys might underestimate good, well-equipped melee characters when you compare your armor and weapon damage output to theirs.  <P>And I think your contributions in a full group are appreciated much more when you are concentrating on using your mana than on meleeing.<P>If you are just getting in an accidental poke between cannibalizes, that's one thing, but you've still significantly reduced your mana regen by not canni-dancing.  <P>Maybe I'm just used to fast-pulling groups and having to do lots of things one right after the other, but it seems to me that my contribution always can be larger in full groups when I use mana rather than melee.
</FONT>
