<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
My take on it as a shaman who enjoys the melee...<P>First off, clearing up some erroneous and misleading statements:<P>-At level 20, the shaman has a weapon skill <BR>-of 84 maxed. This is equal to a level 16 <BR>-warrior<BR>Yes, but pure level does work into the equasion.  Shamans also have the same offensive skills per level as most melee classes.  Also remember that melees cap their weapons skills at 39 for a while while shamans keep going, catching up at 49.<P>-A shaman can melee as well as a druid<BR>Shamans weapons cap at 200, druids at 175.  Shamans also get a MUCH better selection of damaging weapons.  That's one of the biggest reasons shamans are the most melee-oriented caster class: best weapon selection.  (BTW, I believe druids do cap off/def at 200 though, which is the same.  Someone claimed otherwise).<P>-Strength makes up for lack of skill to a <BR>-certain extent<BR>Actually, going back to the first point ... tests have shown that THE primary effect of strength on normal melee combat is that high STR *allows you to hit higher mobs as if they were of a lower level.*  So the buff actually helps there.<P>- Remember, shaman use the same weapon <BR>-formula (4 x level + 4) as intelligence <BR>-casters<BR>Bzz, casters are 3x(level+1)<P>-A twink can wield a weapon just as good as <BR>-anything shaman have, the dark ember<BR>If you're talking about doing significant combat damage, shamans are better off with one of the multiple very good ratio 2hb weapons.  Since we're talking about groups where they're not the tank, anyway, the loss of a shield's ac isn't as vital.<BR>BTW, the Rune Etched Icewurm Fang (12/19, 83 dd proc) is an insane shaman-only spear, and I've seen it on twinkies.<P>-even if you have BEST eqipment for your <BR>-shaman he'll not be over 1.1k<BR>Check again.  I'm at like 1063, and I'm still wearing a ton of pretty 50ish level equipment.  There's an 1100 AC UNBUFFED shaman I know of.<P>Anyway, the point I wanted to make really was that it's not necessarily bad for shamans to melee.  HOWEVER, you should be aware of just how much of a contribution you ARE making and compare to your other options.  In an XP group, I can go hours without meditating.  I'm constantly casting, canning, or using my items, backed up by strong regen.  Given that, it doesn't hurt to turn on attack and whack between casts.<P>There are other situations where you just don't want to act yet.  Might as well attack.  Or there's nothing really efficient to do -- the beauty of melee is that it's mana free, and sometimes it's better to take the free damage rather than DoT, since you may want that mana later.<P>Really, as long as you're doing your job, who cares?  If nothing else, melee is fun =)  And there are a lot of instances where it makes sense, or is at least arguable.
</FONT>
